    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-11T14:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-11T14:30:00-05:00" n="545"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d545">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">352.115/311: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Valencia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-11T15:00:00-04:30"
                            >October 11, 1937—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>797. See despatch X–178, July 31.<note n="10" xml:id="d545fn10">Not
                        printed.</note> A decree dated August 6 was promulgated August 7 creating a
                    commission to examine and report upon the petitions and claims addressed to the
                    Government by foreign entities or persons. The supplementary decree dated August
                    31 was promulgated September 9 designating Alvarez del Vayo as Chairman of the
                    commission and Rafael Ureña, the Secretary General of the Ministry of State, as
                    Vice Chairman.</p>
                <p>In response to representations I was renewing orally at the Ministry of State
                    Saturday, I was informed that the commission in question will soon begin to
                    function.</p>
                <p>Insofar as I am aware all cases in which American interests have been adversely
                    affected have already been informally presented to the Ministry of State by the
                    Embassy (the procedure stipulated by the decree of August 6).</p>
                <p>Repeated to Ambassador Bowers and Paris.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
